A great flood of the {{jalink|Kiso River|Q779607}} in June {{jalink|1586|Q6739}} ({{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 14) significantly changed the river's main channel and split {{jalink|Haguri District|Q1032507}} in two. The region on the right bank became {{jalink|Mino Province|Q864156}} {{jalink|Hashima District|Q11610214}}. Therefore, for parishioners in Hashima District, Mino Province, a branch shrine was established in 1599 ({{jalink|Keichō|Q1328185}} 4) at Minami-oyobi Village, Hashima District (present Masaki-chō Minami-oyobi, {{jalink|Hashima|Q819595}}, {{jalink|Gifu Prefecture|Q131277}}).

In January {{jalink|1946|Q18610}} ({{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 21), it was scheduled for promotion to prefectural shrine, but due to postwar {{jalink|Shinto Directive|Q3029647}}, it was never ranked as kensha.

=== Precinct ===
The spring water that wells up in the precinct is called "Tamanoi Reisen" (Tamanoi spring / Tamai spring), and is the origin of the local place name "Tamanoi." This water is said to have healed the eye disease of {{jalink|Empress Kōmyō|Q837932}}. Faith in healing eye disease continues today.

