'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in Kisogawa-chō (former {{jalink|Kisogawa Town|Q6416838}} in {{jalink|Haguri District|Q1032507}}), {{jalink|Ichinomiya|Q270810}}, {{jalink|Aichi Prefecture|Q80434}}.

It is Anabuto Shrine of Haguri District, {{jalink|Owari Province|Q514506}}, a {{jalink|Shikinaisha|Q11064932|Shikinaisha}} (another theory identifies Anabuto Shrine with {{jalink|Tenjin Shrine (Yanagizu, Gifu)|Q11443286|Tenjin Shrine}} in Gifu City, Gifu Prefecture).

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{jalink|Tamayori-hime|Q56344982|Tamayori-hime-no-Mikoto}}
* Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto (deity of {{jalink|Kamo Wakeikazuchi Shrine|Q700448}})

=== History ===
The founding period is uncertain, but tradition places it in the 6th-century reign of {{jalink|Emperor Kinmei|Q329792}} ({{jalink|539|Q32891}}-{{jalink|571|Q30475}}).

In {{jalink|1090|Q19466}} ({{jalink|Kanji|Q1193874}} 4), Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto was merged and the name changed to Kamo Shrine. In {{jalink|1184|Q19728}} ({{jalink|Juei|Q598057}} 3), {{jalink|Minamoto no Yoritomo|Q242800}} issued prohibitions against misconduct by warriors and provided protection<ref name="kamo">[https://www.aichitabi.com/itimiya/kamo.html Kamo Shrine]</ref>. In the {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, successive lords of the {{jalink|Owari Domain|Q1062072}} donated shrine lands and built a protective cover over the shrine gate<ref name="kamo" />.

A great flood of the {{jalink|Kiso River|Q779607}} in June {{jalink|1586|Q6739}} ({{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 14) significantly changed the river's main channel and split {{jalink|Haguri District|Q1032507}} in two. The region on the right bank became {{jalink|Mino Province|Q864156}} {{jalink|Hashima District|Q11610214}}. Therefore, for parishioners in Hashima District, Mino Province, a branch shrine was established in 1599 ({{jalink|Keichō|Q1328185}} 4) at Minami-oyobi Village, Hashima District (present Masaki-chō Minami-oyobi, {{jalink|Hashima|Q819595}}, {{jalink|Gifu Prefecture|Q131277}}).

In January {{jalink|1946|Q18610}} ({{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 21), it was scheduled for promotion to prefectural shrine, but due to postwar {{jalink|Shinto Directive|Q3029647}}, it was never ranked as kensha.

=== Precinct ===
The spring water that wells up in the precinct is called "Tamanoi Reisen" (Tamanoi spring / Tamai spring), and is the origin of the local place name "Tamanoi." This water is said to have healed the eye disease of {{jalink|Empress Kōmyō|Q837932}}. Faith in healing eye disease continues today.

