'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kisogawa-chō (former {{ill|lt=Kisogawa Town|Q6416838|qid=Q6416838|1=Kisogawa, Aichi}} in {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q1032507|qid=Q1032507|1=Haguri District}}), {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q270810|qid=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}.

It is Anabuto Shrine of Haguri District, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|qid=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} (another theory identifies Anabuto Shrine with {{ill|lt=Tenjin Shrine (Yanagizu, Gifu)|Q11443286|qid=Q11443286|lt=Tenjin Shrine|1=Tenjin Shrine}} in Gifu City, Gifu Prefecture).

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Tamayori-hime|Q56344982|qid=Q56344982|lt=Tamayori-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Tamayori-hime}}
* Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto (deity of {{ill|lt=Kamo Wakeikazuchi Shrine|Q700448|qid=Q700448|1=Kamigamo Shrine}})

=== History ===
The founding period is uncertain, but tradition places it in the 6th-century reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Kinmei|Q329792|qid=Q329792|1=Emperor Kinmei}} ({{ill|lt=539|Q32891|qid=Q32891|1=539}}-{{ill|lt=571|Q30475|qid=Q30475|1=571}}).

In {{ill|lt=1090|Q19466|qid=Q19466|1=1090}} ({{ill|lt=Kanji|Q1193874|qid=Q1193874|1=Kanji (era)}} 4), Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto was merged and the name changed to Kamo Shrine. In {{ill|lt=1184|Q19728|qid=Q19728|1=1184}} ({{ill|lt=Juei|Q598057|qid=Q598057|1=Juei}} 3), {{ill|lt=Minamoto no Yoritomo|Q242800|qid=Q242800|1=Minamoto no Yoritomo}} issued prohibitions against misconduct by warriors and provided protection<ref name="kamo">[https://www.aichitabi.com/itimiya/kamo.html Kamo Shrine]</ref>. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, successive lords of the {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|qid=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}} donated shrine lands and built a protective cover over the shrine gate<ref name="kamo" />.

A great flood of the {{ill|lt=Kiso River|Q779607|qid=Q779607|1=Kiso River}} in June {{ill|lt=1586|Q6739|qid=Q6739|1=1586}} ({{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 14) significantly changed the river's main channel and split {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q1032507|qid=Q1032507|1=Haguri District}} in two. The region on the right bank became {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|qid=Q864156|1=Mino Province}} {{ill|lt=Hashima District|Q11610214|qid=Q11610214|1=Haguri district}}. Therefore, for parishioners in Hashima District, Mino Province, a branch shrine was established in 1599 ({{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 4) at Minami-oyobi Village, Hashima District (present Masaki-chō Minami-oyobi, {{ill|lt=Hashima|Q819595|qid=Q819595|1=Hashima, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|qid=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}).

In January {{ill|lt=1946|Q18610|qid=Q18610|1=1946}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 21), it was scheduled for promotion to prefectural shrine, but due to postwar {{ill|lt=Shinto Directive|Q3029647|qid=Q3029647|1=Shinto Directive}}, it was never ranked as kensha.

=== Precinct ===
The spring water that wells up in the precinct is called "Tamanoi Reisen" (Tamanoi spring / Tamai spring), and is the origin of the local place name "Tamanoi." This water is said to have healed the eye disease of {{ill|lt=Empress Kōmyō|Q837932|qid=Q837932|1=Empress Kōmyō}}. Faith in healing eye disease continues today.

